caption: Why the Title?

!! The Two Components of the Title

David Deutsch chooses this title to highlight a specific transition in human history and a fundamental property of the universe.

!!! 1. The "Beginning" @@(The Enlightenment)@@
For most of history, human societies were '''static'''. Knowledge grew so slowly it was imperceptible, and traditions were enforced through taboos. The "Beginning" refers to the '''Enlightenment''', the moment humanity discovered the "method of finding better explanations." We are at the very start of a journey that shifted us into a '''dynamic''' society.

!!! 2. The "Infinity" (Unbounded Progress)
@@The "Infinity" refers to the fact that knowledge has no upper bound.@@
* '''Universal Explainers:''' Since humans are "universal explainers," our minds can understand anything that is physically understandable. 
* '''No Finality:''' Every problem we solve creates new, more interesting problems. There is no "end of science" or "end of history." 
* '''Infinite Resources:''' We do not run out of resources; we only run out of the knowledge of how to use matter. Since knowledge is infinite, our potential is infinite.

!! Summary
The title is a statement of '''Rational Optimism'''. It suggests that we are not at the peak of our civilization, but rather standing on the threshold of an endless sequence of improvements, provided we maintain the culture of criticism necessary to correct our errors.

> "We are at the beginning of infinity... and we will always be so."